### Describe the bug

When reporting HealthCheckResult.Degraded, and supplying an exception, this exception is never logged (code [here](https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/blob/a450cb69b5e4549f5515cdb057a68771f56cefd7/src/HealthChecks/HealthChecks/src/DefaultHealthCheckService.cs#L241)). This means that I need to have extra logging in my IHealthCheck implementation to get the exception logged when calling HealthCheckResult.Degraded. This seems unneccessary and breaks the expectations of the API. If the HealthCheckResult.Degraded method accepts an exception, I expect it to be logged, at least if it's logged when I call HealthCheckResult.Unhealthy. Please see the steps to reproduce for an example.

### Expected Behavior

I expect the logging behavior to be equal for the calls to HealtCheckResult.Degraded and HealtCheckResult.Unehalthy (at least when it comes to exceptions), to not have to add custom logging in specific cases.

### Steps To Reproduce

When in a IHealthCheck implementation, it is not easy to see that in the call to Degraded in the code below, the exception is not logged:
``` C#
public Task<HealthCheckResult> CheckHealthAsync(HealthCheckContext context, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
  {
    try
    {
      // Call some minor dependency that this service partly depends on
      _minorDependency.CheckStatus();
      return Task.FromResult(HealthCheckResult.Healthy("All good!"));
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
      _logger.LogWarning(ex, "Need to explicitly log here to get the exception logged when calling Degraded");
      // Will not log the exception:
      return Task.FromResult(HealthCheckResult.Degraded($"Minor dependency is down, but I am mostly up", ex));

      // Will log the exception, custom logging not needed:
      return Task.FromResult(HealthCheckResult.Unhealthy($"Minor dependency is down, but I am mostly up", ex));
   }
```


